About This Course

In just over two weeks, you can earn an Abnormal Psychology Certificate by watching entertaining videos and taking short multiple-choice quizzes. Let our instructors introduce you to topics ranging from the psychodynamic model of abnormal behavior to clinical assessment techniques and the characteristics of mental health disorders.

Who's This For?

Social workers, teachers, human service assistants and substance abuse counselors are among the professionals who might benefit from this course.

Prerequisites

There are no prerequisites for this course. However, if you'd like to bolster your psychology background before beginning these lessons, we also have an introductory psychology course as well as courses covering developmental and social psychology.

Benefits of the Certificate

This certificate course might benefit anyone who's interested in learning more about the symptoms, risk factors and treatment options associated with mental health disorders. It might also be of use to individuals looking to enhance their professional credentials or social networking profile. Benefits of this course include:

  • Demonstrates your familiarity with diagnostic criteria and sources for social research data
  • Develops your understanding of the needs of individuals with mental health issues
  • Proves your commitment to life-long learning

Abnormal Psychology Program Breakdown

The 26 chapters included in this course can help you assess the strengths and weaknesses of theoretical models used to explain abnormal behavior. You'll also examine historical perspectives, symptoms and treatment options for a wide range of disorders.

Introduction to Abnormal Psychology

Get an introduction to some of the causes of abnormal behavior. Survey behavioral, biological and cognitive approaches to treatment, among others. Explore issues surrounding the diagnosis of mental health disorders.

Introduction to Research Methods

Discover the characteristics of high-quality research. Examine the differences between qualitative and quantitative research methods. Consider the pros and cons of experimental and non-experimental research designs.

Clinical Research of Abnormal Psychology

Investigate the advantages and disadvantages of case studies, the limitations of correlational research and the uses of experiments to collect social science data. Recognize the significance of random assignments and control groups in experiment design.

The Biological Model of Abnormality

Identify physiological causes of mental illness by examining the function and structure of the nervous and endocrine systems. Study the effectiveness of such treatments as neurosurgery and psychotropic medications.

The Psychodynamic Model of Abnormal Behavior

Survey the psychoanalytic theories of Freud, Erikson, Alder and Jung. Take a closer look at the formation of self-concept. Explore the uses of free association, therapist interpretation and other psychodynamic treatments.

The Behavioral/Learning Model of Abnormal Behavior

Learn how classical and operant conditioning shape behavior. Explore notable experiments demonstrating social cognitive theory and the behavioral model of psychotherapy. Consider the biological limits on conditioning.

The Cognitive Model of Abnormal Behavior

Identify the stages involved in language acquisition, information processing and perceptual development. Learn how our memory works and examine the relationship between thought patterns and abnormal behavior.

The Humanistic-Existential Model of Abnormal Behavior

Recognize Maslow's and Rogers's contributions to humanistic theory. Discover the significance of self-determination and acceptance in the humanistic-existential model of abnormal behavior. Consider the uses of spirituality to treat mental illness.

The Sociocultural Model of Abnormal Behavior

Learn how such factors as labeling, social roles and family systems influence perceptions of abnormality. Examine the types of sociocultural treatments used to address abnormal behavior.

The Diathesis-Stress Model

Identify components of the diathesis-stress model. Find out how genetics and environmental stress affect mental health. Pinpoint factors increasing our vulnerability to psychological disorders.

Clinical Assessment

Investigate the purposes and limitations of clinical interviews as well as behavioral, cognitive, neurological and psychophysiological assessments. Discover the types of intelligence testing and the uses of observational and field research.

Introduction to Anxiety Disorders

Recognize the causes of generalized anxiety disorder and explore the symptoms of panic disorder and agoraphobia. Take a look at phobias and obsessive-compulsive disorder as well as trauma-related disorders, such as PTSD.

Mood Disorders of Abnormal Psychology

Examine treatments for mood disorders ranging from depressive disorder to bipolar disorder. Study triggers for suicidal thoughts and the measures used to address their underlying causes.

Stress Disorders

Consider the relationship between emotions, the fight or flight response and stress. Learn what causes acute stress disorders and psychophysiological disorders. Assess the uses of positive psychology to treat them.

Somatoform Disorders in Abnormal Psychology

Examine characteristics of somatoform disorders, including pain disorder, conversion disorder and hypochondriasis. Examine body dysmorphic disorder as well as undifferentiated somatoform disorders.

Dissociative Disorders in Psychology

Learn to recognize dissociative amnesia and dissociative fugue disorder. Identify symptoms of multiple personality and depersonalization disorders.

Eating Disorders in Abnormal Psychology

Study the prognoses for patients with anorexia, bulimia and binge eating disorder. Find out how sociocultural and genetic factors can increase the risk of developing an eating disorder.

Sexual and Gender Identity Disorders

Survey a wide range of sexual dysfunctions, including desire and sexual pain disorders as well as paraphilias. Examine the features of sex therapy and the treatment options for gender identity disorder.

Substance Use Disorders

Differentiate between substance use, abuse and dependence. Identify characteristics of dependence on depressants, stimulants and hallucinogens. Explore some of the therapeutic approaches used to treat substance-related disorders.

Psychotic Disorders

Examine the causes and phases of schizophrenia, and assess the impact of genetics and the social environment on this disorder. Take a look at other delusional mental health disorders, such as schizoaffective disorder and brief psychotic disorder.

Cognitive Disorders in Abnormal Psychology

Learn how to differentiate between delirium, dementia and Alzheimer's disease. Study symptoms of amnesia and substance-induced cognitive disorders. Examine the onset of mental health problems in late adulthood.

Life-Span Development Disorders

Investigate the development of mental health disorders in childhood and adolescence. Consider the effect of emotional and behavioral disorders, like autism, Asperger's and ADHD, on learning. Identify prevention techniques and treatments for mental retardation.

Personality Disorders in Abnormal Psychology

Recognize the characteristics of cluster A, B and C personality disorders, such as paranoid, schizoid, erratic and obsessive-compulsive personality disorders. Identify some of the challenges psychologists face when making these diagnoses.

Factitious Disorders

Survey the types of factitious disorders and their symptoms. Examine some of their causes and treatment options.

Treatment in Abnormal Psychology

Assess the effectiveness of individual, group and biological therapy as well psychiatric drugs. Discover some of the community approaches used to treat and prevent mental health issues.

Legal and Ethical Issues in Abnormal Psychology

Examine the use of psychological evaluations in the courtroom and consider the legal obligations of therapists. Develop an awareness of the rights of mentally ill patients. Get an overview of domestic and international efforts to improve mental health.
